2195B - Heapify 1
Let us look at which elements can be rearranged freely:
$$$a_1,a_2,a_4,a_8,\ldots$$$ can be rearranged freely;
$$$a_3,a_6,a_{12},\ldots$$$ can be rearranged freely;
$$$a_5,a_{10},\ldots$$$ can be rearranged freely;
$$$a_7,a_{14},\ldots$$$ can be rearranged freely;
$$$\ldots$$$
The lexicographically smallest achievable sequence would be found by sorting each of those subsequences one by one. You can achieve an $$$\mathcal{O}(n)$$$ solution by checking if each of the subsequences can be sorted into the elements required in those positions.
However, a solution under the given constraint does not have to be too complex. In fact, even if you sort each subsequence using bubble sort, the worst case time complexity would be $$$\mathcal{O}(n \log n)$$$. Remember that the longest one of these subsequences (containing $$$a_1$$$) has length $$$\left \lfloor \log_2 n \right \rfloor + 1$$$. Let's place squares with side length equal to subsequence length aligned to the $$$x$$$-axis. Then, these squares would easily fit in a rectangle of width $$$n$$$ and height $$$\left \lfloor \log_2 n \right \rfloor + 1$$$. Therefore, the sum of $$$k^2$$$ over all subsequence lengths $$$k$$$ follows $$$\mathcal{O}(n \log n)$$$ asymptotically.
The proof for bubble sort working in $$$\mathcal{O}(n \log n)$$$ time on $$$n=15$$$
The problem is solved in $$$\mathcal{O}(n \log n)$$$ time.
